JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand weakened slightly on Thursday, giving back gains from recent sessions as investors took profits as a mood of risk aversion spread through global markets.At 0645 GMT the rand had slipped 0.35% to 13.5000 per dollar compared to a close of 13.4525 overnight in New York.The rand was underpinned by slightly improved sentiment after parliament said on Wednesday a motion of no-confidence in President Jacob Zuma has been postponed until a court decides whether the vote should be taken by secret ballot.Traders said lingering political uncertainty was set to limit gains in the local currency.Mining production data for February due at 1100 GMT, expected to show continued recovery in the sector.Stocks set to open lower at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index down 0.2 percent.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 fell 4.5 basis points to 8.825%.